diff:1620530496:1620530496:=1,44d0%0a%3c :Category: Varia%0a%3c :Expansion: Imperative form in Japanese%0a%3c :Author: MarkC%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.ShowingPersonalityThroughLanguageInTV|ShowingPersonalityThroughLanguageInTV]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.ayush_d|ayush_d]]%0a%3c :Section: F%0a%3c :Completed: 08.05.2021 - 20:21%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Another way politeness is used in the Japanese language is how requests are usually stated. In Japanese, morphology in verbs contains an imperative form of the verb which has the semantic meaning of a command regarding that verb. However, the pragmatics of this form is that its considered very impolite and should only be used by those of a higher social standing to those of a lower social standing. Even so, due to its authoritative connotations, this form is rarely every used in practice in Japanese. Instead requests are generally stated by conjugating the verb to the "te" form (connective form) and appending "kudasai" which roughly translates to please in Japanese. %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.tofugu.com/japanese-grammar/verb-command-form-ro/%0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.nhk.or.jp/lesson/english/teacher/8.html%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
